    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3459650788" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3459650788" />
    <a title="Mari" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/84693823-mari"><img alt="Mari" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1618060489p2/84693823.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3459650788?book_show_action=true">Jul 26, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mari" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mari" href="/user/show/84693823-mari">Mari</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer3459650788&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3459650788" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3526297471151050946">Review added 7/27/20<br/><br/>This book was published by scholastic and obviously meant for a young audience, so readers who are used to Alice Hoffman&apos;s adult works might be taken aback by the comparatively simplistic style. In a way, it reads like a fairytale or what I call a &apos;campfire story&apos;--a story that relies heavily on narrative, with little dialogue. From a technical standpoint, it felt a little unpolished and I definitely prefer her later works.<br/><br/>I didn&apos;t go into this story expecting it to be an all</span>
  <span id="freeText3526297471151050946" style="display:none">Review added 7/27/20<br /><br />This book was published by scholastic and obviously meant for a young audience, so readers who are used to Alice Hoffman's adult works might be taken aback by the comparatively simplistic style. In a way, it reads like a fairytale or what I call a 'campfire story'--a story that relies heavily on narrative, with little dialogue. From a technical standpoint, it felt a little unpolished and I definitely prefer her later works.<br /><br />I didn't go into this story expecting it to be an allegory for 9/11 and the events following it, but I knew as soon as I read this quote:<br /><br /><blockquote>People who were close by said they could see people jumping from the buildings, like silver birds, like bright diamonds.</blockquote><br /><br />I recognized this because in high school, we read a firsthand account of the attacks that described the exact same thing. I flipped back to see when the book was published, and sure enough, it had originally been written in 2003. Alice Hoffman's website also specifies that this book was written after 9/11, and as such, I cannot divorce the connection between the terrorist attacks and the book. This review will be written in this context.<br /><br />The book feels longer than it actually is because of the slow pace, the relative lack of dialogue, and how heavily it focuses on the thoughts of the protagonist. This normally bothers me when I'm reading, but this time I didn't mind. It's a very interesting look into the trauma and resulting distrust that had been so prevalent at the time: how the city in the book was destroyed is described as it pretty much exploding and leaving the world burnt and covered in ash. <br /><br />Interestingly enough, we never journey outside of the city and Green's village--there are simply implications that the world is no longer what it once was. No one from the outside comes to their aid, and 'the Horde', the people who destroyed the city, are a constant looming threat. This is pretty accurate to how I remember everyone feeling after the event: are we going to be attacked again? What's going on?<br /><br />I also found what I believe to be references to Islamophobia throughout the book. For example:<br /><br /><blockquote>While I was getting ready to go I heard the shopkeeper and his wife talk about the people who had destroyed the city. Some of them had been living among us, pretending to be good neighbors. Their wives had shopped in our markets. Their children had gone to our schools, eaten our bread, played in our streets.</blockquote><br /><br />On page 131, the Horde is described as having infiltrated the city and village for years, simply for the purpose of destroying it for religious purposes and so on. They are even described as having a different language. The protagonist buys into this, as so many others do, and as I believe so many Americans did after the attacks. <br /><br />However, by the end of the book, it is revealed that Green's people and Diamond's people are not so different after all--symbolized by them having one half of a heart tattooed onto their chest--and at the end they both speak each other's languages and live peacefully together.<br /><br />As I was very young when 9/11 occurred, so there's little I can say except the feelings of uncertainty and being in danger are very accurate to what Americans felt after 9/11. However, as I am white, I cannot reliably provide any opinions about this interpretation of Islamophobia. I believe someone who is Muslim and/or was old enough to have a more nuanced view of the political atmosphere in the early 2000s would be better at articulating this. I can only point out the connections I see to real life events and hope that someone else can interpret them for me.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3526297471151050946" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

