<div id="review_2461796289" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2461796289" />
    <a title="Carol Albert" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/46621745-carol-albert"><img alt="Carol Albert" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2461796289?book_show_action=true">Jul 18, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Carol Albert" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Carol Albert" href="/user/show/46621745-carol-albert">Carol Albert</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/46621745-carol-albert?shelf=young-adult">young-adult</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2461796289" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer168568504072201592">This is a YA book that would be enjoyed and appreciated by any adult who savors a story beautifully told. It is 2 novellas combined: &quot;Green Angel&quot; and &quot;Green Witch,&quot; both which have been published separately previously. Both tell the story of Green, as she experiences and recovers from the terrorist attack on the city across the river, which killed her entire family. At first, I thought the attack was referring to 9/11 in NYC, but the facts don&apos;t match. Perhaps it was inspiration for Hoffman. Th</span>
  <span id="freeText168568504072201592" style="display:none">This is a YA book that would be enjoyed and appreciated by any adult who savors a story beautifully told. It is 2 novellas combined: "Green Angel" and "Green Witch," both which have been published separately previously. Both tell the story of Green, as she experiences and recovers from the terrorist attack on the city across the river, which killed her entire family. At first, I thought the attack was referring to 9/11 in NYC, but the facts don't match. Perhaps it was inspiration for Hoffman. The first part was published first in 2003, two years after 9/11. She is alone, and changes, drawing into herself, so much that she loses her name. She becomes Ash. Everyone she encounters is also dealing with the after-effects of the disaster. After Hoffman paints a picture of total despair, she returns to the story and her characters find hope. In the end, Green is once more Green; neither an angel nor a witch.<br /><br />I think I will hang onto this book to re-read in the future. It is not only a beautiful story, but also it may have some gardening tips! As soon as Green shared that her mother taught her vinegar on roses kept beetles away, I went out to my garden and poured some vinegar water on them! (Within a week, I saw my first Japanese beetle of the year on a rose, so I'm not sure this can be taken seriously.) Later in the story, Green said that garlic or something else kept aphids off of roses. </span>
  <a data-text-id="168568504072201592" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


