<div id="review_3985769119" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3985769119" />
    <a title="Tracy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2455706-tracy"><img alt="Tracy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1615038154p2/2455706.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3985769119?book_show_action=true">May 17, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tracy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tracy" href="/user/show/2455706-tracy">Tracy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3985769119" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12263988254309660978">A friend gave me a copy of Green Heart before major surgery. Around the one year anniversary, I decided it was time to read the book. I wish I read it sooner! YA books always have some hope. <br/><br/>&quot;Dreams are like air. They never leave you. It takes less than nothing to begin. Start with a pile of rocks.&quot; (129)<br/><br/>It was a beautiful post-apocalyptic fairy tale, about a girl (Green) who lost everything, built a hard exterior as Ash, then slowly learned how healing storytelling can be. The loneliness Green </span>
  <span id="freeText12263988254309660978" style="display:none">A friend gave me a copy of Green Heart before major surgery. Around the one year anniversary, I decided it was time to read the book. I wish I read it sooner! YA books always have some hope. <br /><br />"Dreams are like air. They never leave you. It takes less than nothing to begin. Start with a pile of rocks." (129)<br /><br />It was a beautiful post-apocalyptic fairy tale, about a girl (Green) who lost everything, built a hard exterior as Ash, then slowly learned how healing storytelling can be. The loneliness Green felt after the fire brought back early pandemic memories--I do not think I could have read this book last year. <br /><br />"There was the world waiting outside, aching and ruined, but beautiful all the same." (110)<br /><br />I was imagining a young Kristen Stewart (Twilight era) as Green/Ash. The vivid colors and tastes in the book capture one's imagination, as well as the poetic language. I loved the descriptions of creating the paper for each person's unique story.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12263988254309660978" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


